         <entry xml:id="Slips_BroadfordMFarmerslips-idp161827920">
            <form>
               <orth>mògais</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Notes: a messy mixture, e.g. of food.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="Slips_BroadfordMFarmerslips-idp161829432">
            <form>
               <orth>rionnag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Notes: ‘a spark of life in the fire.’</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="Slips_BroadfordMFarmerslips-idp161830944">
            <form>
               <orth>plìon</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Notes: a smile, smirk.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="Slips_BroadfordMFarmerslips-idp161832456">
            <form>
               <orth>sgaimeic</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quotation: sgaimeic (hd) – pronounced as if with -hd. Notes: stressed syllable has /ɛ/ sound. Has general meaning of ‘a mess’. Could be used of foods mixed together which aren’t usually mixed. Phrase ‘Rinn e s. dheth’ could be used of someone who’s messed some job up. [NOTES: on this slip ‘Broadford’ was crossed out and replaced with ‘Breakish’.]</def>
         </entry>
